Methods¶

For the variables, we did four pair. For all four sets of data, we each did one scatter plot, one scatter plot with trend line, two box- plots for each variable and two histograms for each variable. We did scatterplot to see the relationship between the two variables, and the trend line helps us to see the relationship more clearly and identify if it is a strong or weak relationship. We did box-plots because it can help us to see the range, the median of the data and since it is separated by a categorical variable, we can discover the relationship between the continuous variable and the categorical variable. We did the histogram because it allows us to see the maximum and minimum for each variable.

First variable¶

The first pair is the male earnings and female earnings. We collected the data from the HDI dataset. The data could be conducted through surveys, social research or statistic report from authentic companies. This pair of variable is important because it can show the difference between female and male. The equality between female and male is a very controversial topic right now, it is crucial for us to find the gap through data comparison. For the outside source, we found that there is an EqualPay Act since 1963. Since then, the United States labor law abandoned the wage gap between male and female. But even with the act, we can still see disparity on salaries between male and female nowadays.

Hypothesis¶

We assume that male earns more than female do. We do not think there will be an obvious relationship for scatterplot for that they might not influence each other directly, it is just a phenomenon.

<font color = "red"> Okay, but how else might you compare these? Why would there be a relationship between them? What about mean, median, mode or descriptive comparisons from one group to the next?</font>

There is not a strong relationship, the plots are very scattered and it is hard to see the relationship.

In [5]:
ggplot(data = HDI, mapping = aes(x = Earnings_M, y = Earnings_F)) + 
  geom_point() +
    geom_smooth()

`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

With the trend line, we are able to see the relationship more clearly. At the beginning, the more the female earns, the less the male earns, but as the graph develop, we can see that the more female earns, the more male earns. And despite the female salary is on the rise, male earns more than female.

Second pair¶

The second pair of data is the annual cost of public schools and the annual cost for private schools. The data could be collected from school surveys, educational organization and social survey. This pair of data is important because education is an essential part of the growth of society and it is important for people to understand better if everyone has the same opportunity. This pair of data allows us to see the difference of cost between public schools and private schools. Private schools cost more than public schools, however, in one of the sources we found from Washington Post, the author discusses whether private schools give better education than public schools. He questioned the difference and showed evidence that sometimes public schools students outperform the students from private schools.

Hypothesis¶

We assume that private school cost more than that of public schools. We also think that on the graph, its going to show that the cost for public and private schools increase over time because the tuition for both type should be increasing every year.

There is a fairly direct relationship for the annual cost of four-year public schools and private schools. We can see that the cost for both types of schools are gradually increasing.

Third Pair¶

The third pair of data we picked is suicide rate and rape rate. The data could be collected from social surveys, statistic from the police office, record from suicide helping center and hospital. This is important because it show the relationship between rape and suicide, it show wether the trauma can cause a deadly consequence. In one of the sources we got, a girl who was raped committed suicide because of the torment she had to go through while confronting her attacker. It shows that the traumatic experience can learn to very bad consequence.

Hypothesis¶

We assume that the higher the rape rate, the higher the suicide rate.

There is a fairly direct relationship. We can see that the higher the rape rate, the higher the suiciderate.

In [21]:
ggplot(data = HDI, mapping = aes(x = SUICIDERATE, y = RAPERATE)) + 
  geom_point() +
    geom_smooth()

`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

With the line, we can be more sure that the rape rate and suiciderate directly influence each other, The higher the rape rate, the higher the suicide rate.

From the boxplot catagorized by region, we can see that the rape rate is the highest at Midwest and the lowest at NorthEast.

From the boxplot catagorized by region we can see that the suicide rate is the highest at west and the lowest at northeast. This is reasonable because the suicide rate is the second highest for the region midwest. Even though the suicide rate for midwest is not the highest like the rape rate, we think that it is close enough to explain the relationshio between rape rate and suicide rate since it is the second highest and the lowest rate region matches for the two boxplot.

For the histogram, we can see that the mode for rape rate is around 26%. There are very few that is above 60% and below 20%.

Fourth Variable¶

The fourth pair of data is labor force and GDP_PC. The data could be collected from companies that required labor force, and yearly report of the economic growth. This is important because it shows how labor force and GDP affect each other and the relationship between them. It can help us understand if labor force is benefitting or impeding the growth of GDP. From the website world-watch, we found proof that labor force helps the growth of GDP and economic expansion.

Hypothesis¶

We assume that the higher the labor force, the higher the GDP_PC.

From the scatterplot, we can see a relationship but not a strong one since the slope is low and flat.

In [30]:
ggplot(data = HDI, mapping = aes(x = LABORFORCE, y = GDP_PC)) + 
  geom_point() +
    geom_smooth()

`geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

With the line, we can see that The higher the laborforce, the higher the GDP. They might not have a very strong relationship but they do inlfuence each other in some degree.

In [33]:
plot_grid(b1, b2)

From the boxplot catagorized by region, we can see that the south has the lowest GPD_PC, which matches with our last boxplot of South having the lowest laborforce. And the northeast has the highest GDP_PC. Even though midwest had the highest laborforce and does not have the highest GDP_PC, the GDP_PC for midwest is very close to that of the NorthEast, so we think the discrepancy can be ignored. The two boxplots show that the higher the laborforce, the higher the GDP_PC.

from the histogram, we can see that the mode for laborforce is around 74 and 77.

Conclusion¶

The hypothesis for all four sets of data match with our results. Each of these data sets show a certain relationship between the two variables. They tell us how do they affect each other. By looking at those visualization, we learned that how diverse social phenomenon can be linked to each other and we learned better at using the R-notebook to show visualization and present variables in different ways. By choosing different visualizations, people can discover more intriguing ways to introduce rather boring data so that it can help people be more interested in learning them. In the future, it should be interesting to investigate more in-depth on what kind of trauma does rape create and how differently do these traumas influence the suicide rate. For example, do they cause trauma for the vicim at court, at home, the pressure from family or the pressure from media and peers.
